The most closely related species are: Dobsonia viridis, Epomophorus wahlbergi, Syconycteris australis, and Cynopterus sphinx.

This phylogeny illustrates the evolutionary relationships of ACE2 genes among different bat species. Because ACE2 serves as the receptor for SARS-like viruses, comparing these sequences can help identify which bat species may be more likely to interact with similar viruses.
